However, the\nradio spectral index maps show a variation of spectral indices with flatter\nspectra associated with star-forming regions and steeper spectra in galaxy\noutskirts and, in particular, in extra-planar regions. We found that galaxies\nwith high star-formation rates (SFR) have steeper radio spectra; we find\nsimilar correlations with galaxy size, mass, and rotation speed. Conclusions.\nGalaxies that are larger and more massive are better electron calorimeters,\nmeaning that the CRE lose a higher fraction of their energy within the\ngalaxies. This explains the super-linear radio-SFR relation, with more massive,\nstar-forming galaxies being radio bright. We propose a semi-calorimetric\nradio-SFR relation, which employs the galaxy mass as a proxy for the\ncalorimetric efficiency.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 1 Apr 2022 18:00:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-10"}
